body:
Alright, finally broke down and tried this in C:

```C
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

int main(char **argv, int* argc) {
  double x = 1.0;
  double y = 0.1;
  double z;
  double w;

  printf("%.55f\n", fmod(1.0, 0.1));
  w = modf(x/y, &z);
  printf("%.55f\n", w);
  printf("%.55f\n", z);
}
```
which prints out:
```
0.0999999999999999500399638918679556809365749359130859375
0.0000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000
10.0000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000
```
So pretty much what's been observed thus far. Looks like the two code paths here:

https://github.com/ruby/ruby/blob/ruby_1_9_2/numeric.c#L770

aren't *quite* equivalent due to rounding of intermediate results. See this for way more detail than you probably want:

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4218961/why-fmod1-0-0-1-1

TL;DR of the above: `%` for floating-point is cranky, and WILL bite you.
